Here is a concise, high-density guide to Seaborn, the go-to Python library for making beautiful, statistical data visualizations.What is Seaborn?Built on top of Matplotlib, Seaborn closely integrates with Pandas data structures. It automates the painful parts of data visualization—like color mapping, facetting, and statistical aggregation—allowing you to create publication-quality plots with just a few lines of code.Key FeaturesDataset-Oriented API: You can plot directly using DataFrame columns (x="column_1", y="column_2").Built-in Statistical Estimation: Automatically computes and displays linear regressions, error bars, and confidence intervals.Sophisticated Themes: Offers beautiful default styles and color palettes designed for clarity and accessibility.The Core Functional StructureSeaborn’s plotting functions are divided into two main categories: Aesthetic/Figure-level functions (which manage their own figures) and Axes-level functions (which draw onto specific matplotlib axes).Here are the three primary modules you will use:1. Relational Plots (Visualizing Relationships)Used to analyze how variables correlate with each other.sns.scatterplot() / sns.relplot(kind="scatter"): Showcases the relationship between two continuous variables.sns.lineplot() / sns.relplot(kind="line"): Ideal for tracking tracking changes over time or continuous intervals.2. Distribution Plots (Visualizing Data Spread)Used to understand the dataset's shape, center, and variance.sns.histplot() / sns.displot(kind="hist"): Traditional histogram showing frequency counts.sns.kdeplot() / sns.displot(kind="kde"): Kernel Density Estimate for a smooth, continuous probability curve.sns.ecdfplot() / sns.displot(kind="ecdf"): Empirical Cumulative Distribution Functions.3. Categorical Plots (Visualizing Variables by Group)Used when one of your primary variables is discrete/categorical.sns.boxplot() / sns.catplot(kind="box"): Shows the median, quartiles, and outliers.sns.violinplot() / sns.catplot(kind="violin"): Combines a boxplot with a KDE plot to show the underlying distribution shape.sns.barplot() / sns.catplot(kind="bar"): Displays point estimates (usually the mean) and error bars.5-Line Quickstart Cheat SheetTo give you an idea of how clean the syntax is, here is a standard setup for a scatter plot with a linear regression line:Pythonimport seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1. Load a built-in dataset
tips = sns.load_dataset("tips")

# 2. Set the aesthetic theme
sns.set_theme(style="darkgrid")

# 3. Create a statistical plot
sns.lmplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip", hue="smoker")

# 4. Show the plot
plt.show()
Summary Cheat Sheet: relplot vs displot vs catplotWhen working with complex, multi-plot layouts, use Seaborn's figure-level functions. They handle facets (subplots) effortlessly using the col and row arguments:Figure-Level FunctionDefault KindBest Used Forsns.relplot()scatterExamining correlations between continuous data points across subgroups.sns.displot()histChecking for skewness, modality, and data spread.sns.catplot()stripComparing distributions or aggregates across different categories.Pro-Tip: If you need to map complex pairwise relationships across an entire dataset quickly, use sns.pairplot(df). It generates a matrix of histograms and scatterplots for every numerical column in your dataframe with a single line of code.

The 6 Classes of Plots in Seaborna. Relational PlotsUsed to examine relationships and correlations between continuous numerical variables.scatterplot: Plots individual data points; perfect for checking clusters and trends.lineplot: Connects data points sequentially; ideal for time-series data.b. Distribution PlotsUsed to inspect how a single continuous variable (or pair of variables) is distributed.Histogram (histplot): Splits data into bins and counts frequencies.KDE (kdeplot): Smooths out data to show a continuous probability density curve.RugPlot (rugplot): Draws marginal ticks along an axis to show the exact location of individual data points.c. Categorical PlotsUsed when your data involves discrete categories or groups.Barplot: Shows point estimates (usually the mean) with error bars.countplot: A histogram for categorical data; simply counts the number of occurrences per category.Boxplot: Displays the 5-number summary (median, quartiles, outliers).Violin (violinplot): Combines a boxplot with a KDE to show the distribution shape.swarmplot: A categorical scatter plot where points are adjusted so they don't overlap, revealing the exact distribution density.d. Matrix PlotsUsed to plot entire multi-dimensional datasets or tables of numbers using color intensity.Heatmap: A 2D grid where values are represented by colors (e.g., visualizing a correlation matrix).clustermap: A heatmap that uses hierarchical clustering to group similar rows and columns together, accompanied by a dendrogram (tree diagram).e. Regression PlotsUsed to map relationships while adding an automated statistical model layer.regplot: Plots a scatter plot but automatically calculates and draws a linear regression line along with a 95% confidence interval band.f. Multiplot (Grid Plots)To complete your note: Multiplots are grid-based layouts that allow you to combine multiple subplots into a single figure for deeper exploratory analysis. The key functions here are:pairplot: Automatically plots a pairwise matrix of scatter plots and histograms for every single numeric column in a DataFrame.jointplot: Creates a central bivariate plot (like a scatter or hex plot) flanked by marginal univariate plots (histograms/KDEs) on the top and right margins.FacetGrid: The underlying engine that lets you map any custom plotting function across a grid of subplots based on categorical features (using rows and columns).Quick Reference MapClassKey GoalExample FunctionRelationalCheck trends / correlationsns.scatterplot()DistributionSee data spread / peakssns.histplot()CategoricalCompare grouped datasns.boxplot()MatrixVisualize 2D tables/matricessns.heatmap()RegressionAdd linear trendlinessns.regplot()MultiplotCombine multiple views/gridssns.pairplot()